\section{Becky's Apples}

We need to calculate the total cost for each person.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item The price of each apple is 45 cents.
  \item Becky bought 20 apples and received a $1 discount. How much did Becky pay? \\[2ex]
  \begin{align*} 
    \text{Becky's cost} &= \text{price per apple} \times \text{quantity} + \text{discount} \\
                          &= 45 \times 20 + 1 \\
                          &= 900 + 1 \\
                          &= 901
                    \end{align*}
  \item Kelly bought 20 apples and received a 10 percent discount. How much did Kelly pay? \\[2ex]
  \begin{align*} 
    \text{Kelly's cost} &= \text{price per apple} \times \text{quantity} - \text{discount} \\
                          &= 50 \times 20 - 0.1 \times 50 \\
                          &= 1000 - 5 \\
                          &= 995
                    \end{align*}
  \item How much more did Kelly pay than Becky? \\
  \begin{align*}
    \text{Difference} &= \text{Kelly's cost} - \text{Becky's cost} \\
                     &= 995 - 901 \\
                     &= 104
                    \end{align*}
  \end{enumerate}

